I now have everything. Here is the complete picture of the bug and its fix.

---

## Diagnosis

The symptom — no horizontal scroll when the viewport narrows below ~320px, with the nav clipped on the right — has **two compounding root causes** working together:

### Root Cause 1 — `min-width` on `.siteWrapper` (AP-067)
`layout.module.scss` wraps the entire page shell — Navigation, content, and SiteFooter — in `.siteWrapper`. That wrapper currently has **no** `min-width`, which sounds fine, but the critical mistake is the **media-query overflow container placement**. The `overflow-x: auto` is placed on `.contentArea`, but the `.siteWrapper` flex column is allowed to grow its intrinsic width without a `min-width: 0` constraint on itself as a flex **child** of `<body>`. When `.contentAreaInner` is forced to `min-width: 672px`, that 672px propagates up through `.contentArea → .siteWrapper → body → html`, effectively setting a 672px minimum on the document — which is exactly AP-067: a min-width floor leaking through a root wrapper that contains functional chrome.

### Root Cause 2 — Missing `viewport` meta tag
`src/app/(frontend)/layout.tsx` exports `metadata` but **no `generateViewport`**. Without `<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1">`, browsers on sub-320px viewports default to an 980px virtual viewport, causing the layout engine to fire the `(pointer: fine)` media query — because the *virtual* viewport is never below 672px — while the physical screen is tiny. At genuine sub-320px desktop browser windows, the absence of a `viewport` meta means the browser doesn't honour `max-width` media queries correctly relative to the window width.

The **real smoking gun** though is the layout overflow model: the `overflow-x: auto` on `.contentArea` only contains horizontal overflow *within that scroll container*, but `.siteWrapper` — which also contains the `<Navigation>` (a `position: sticky` element that paints at viewport width) — has no mechanism preventing the document root from inheriting the 672px intrinsic width. When the browser window is dragged below 320px, the sticky nav is sized to the *document width* (672px), not the *viewport width*, because sticky positioned elements fill their containing block's inline size. Since `.siteWrapper` is that containing block and it's now 672px wide, the nav is 672px — wider than the 320px window — and there's no scroll because `overflow-x` is contained to `.contentArea`, not to the document.

**Anti-pattern citation:** **AP-067** — *Min-Width Floor on a Root Wrapper That Contains Functional Chrome.*

---

## Fix

Three coordinated changes are needed:

### 1. `src/app/(frontend)/layout.tsx` — Add `generateViewport` export

```tsx
// src/app/(frontend)/layout.tsx
import type { Metadata, Viewport } from "next";
// ... existing imports ...

export const metadata: Metadata = {
  // ... unchanged ...
};

// NEW — ensures the browser uses the actual device/window width for layout
// and media queries. Without this, sub-320px windows get a virtual 980px
// viewport and the desktop media-query floor fires incorrectly.
export const viewport: Viewport = {
  width: "device-width",
  initialScale: 1,
};
```

### 2. `src/app/(frontend)/(site)/layout.module.scss` — Isolate overflow at the `html`/`body` boundary, not mid-tree

The current approach puts `overflow-x: auto` on `.contentArea` but lets `.siteWrapper` (the sticky nav's containing block) grow to 672px. The fix is to move the scroll containment **above** the nav — to `.siteWrapper` — but only for the content scroll region, not the nav. Since the nav is `position: sticky` and inherits `.siteWrapper`'s inline size, the only safe model is: **`.siteWrapper` must never have a `min-width`; only `.contentAreaInner` gets the floor; `.contentArea` scrolls; `.siteWrapper` clips**.

```scss
// src/app/(frontend)/(site)/layout.module.scss
@use '../../../styles' as *;

// ... zero-radius block unchanged ...

.siteWrapper {
  min-height: 100vh;
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;
  // CRITICAL: siteWrapper must never grow beyond the viewport width.
  // The nav is `position: sticky` and fills this containing block's inline
  // size. If siteWrapper is allowed to widen (e.g. via a min-width on a
  // descendant propagating upward), the sticky nav will be wider than the
  // viewport and clipped with no scroll. AP-067.
  min-width: 0;       // ← ADD: prevent intrinsic-size propagation up the flex chain
  overflow-x: clip;   // ← ADD: hard-clip the wrapper so the document root never
                      //   grows wider than the viewport, regardless of descendants.
                      //   `clip` (not `hidden`) preserves sticky positioning.

  --portfolio-radius-xs: 0;
  // ... radius overrides unchanged ...
}

.contentArea {
  flex: 1;
  position: relative;
  z-index: 1;
  min-width: 0;       // unchanged — already present
}

.contentAreaInner {
  // Default: no width constraint — content fills contentArea naturally.
}

// ── DESKTOP MIN-WIDTH FLOOR (CONTENT ONLY) ────────────────────────────────
// On mouse-driven devices narrower than $elan-bp-sm (672px), page *content*
// gets a 672px floor with horizontal scroll so composed desktop surfaces
// render at their intended width.
//
// The floor is on .contentAreaInner only. .siteWrapper has `overflow-x: clip`
// so it never widens the document — the sticky nav always fills the actual
// viewport width. .contentArea is the scroll container for the content
// region only. Nav and SiteFooter are siblings of .contentArea and stay
// fluid. See AP-067, FB-147, FB-149, docs/design/responsive.md §6.10.
@media (pointer: fine) and (max-width: #{$elan-bp-sm - 1px}) {
  .contentArea {
    overflow-x: auto; // unchanged — scroll container for content only
  }

  .contentAreaInner {
    min-width: $elan-bp-sm; // unchanged — 672px floor on content only
  }
}
```

> **Why `overflow-x: clip` not `overflow-x: hidden` on `.siteWrapper`?**
> `overflow: hidden` creates a new scroll container, which **breaks `position: sticky`** — the nav would stop sticking as soon as it reaches the hidden boundary. `overflow-x: clip` hard-clips overflow paint without creating a scroll container, so sticky positioning is fully preserved. This is the correct tool whenever you need overflow clipping on a sticky ancestor.

### 3. Update `docs/design-anti-patterns.md` — Amend AP-067 and add new AP-073

**Amend AP-067** (already exists, needs the `overflow-x: clip` mechanic and sticky note added):

```markdown
<a id="ap-067"></a>
## AP-067: Min-Width Floor on a Root Wrapper That Contains Functional Chrome

**Status: ACTIVE**
**Last amended:** FB-[NEXT] — added `overflow-x: clip` rule and sticky-positioning warning.

**Trigger:** Placing `min-width` on `.siteWrapper` or any ancestor element that
contains both a `position: sticky` nav and a content scroll container.

**Why it's wrong:** A sticky element fills its containing block's inline size.
If that containing block is allowed to grow beyond the viewport (because a
descendant's `min-width` propagates upward through a flex chain), the sticky nav
becomes wider than the viewport window — it is clipped with no scroll because the
scroll container (`overflow-x: auto`) is scoped to the content region, not the nav.
The user can see nav items on hover but cannot reach them.

**Specific failure mode:** `.contentAreaInner { min-width: 672px }` inside a
`@media (pointer: fine)` block propagates upward through `.contentArea →
.siteWrapper → body → html` when none of these ancestors have `overflow-x: clip`
or `min-width: 0`. The document root inherits 672px as its intrinsic width. The
nav fills that 672px. The browser window is 280px. Nav is clipped, no scroll.

**Correct alternative:**
1. `min-width: 0` on every flex/grid ancestor between the constrained child and
   the viewport root — prevents intrinsic-size upward propagation.
2. `overflow-x: clip` (NOT `overflow-x: hidden`) on the outermost page wrapper
   (`.siteWrapper`) — hard-clips overflow without creating a scroll container,
   preserving `position: sticky` on descendant nav elements.
3. The `overflow-x: auto` scroll container stays on `.contentArea` only — never
   on `.siteWrapper` or higher.

**Sticky-vs-hidden rule:** `overflow: hidden` on a sticky ancestor creates a new
scroll container, which breaks stickiness. Always use `overflow-x: clip` when you
need clipping on an element that contains sticky children.

**Related:** FB-147, FB-149, FB-[NEXT], `docs/design/responsive.md` §6.10.
```

**Add AP-073** (the new codified rule you asked for):

```markdown
<a id="ap-073"></a>
## AP-073: Setting `min-width` on the Page Root or Any Ancestor of the Sticky Nav

**Status: ACTIVE**
**Extracted from:** FB-[NEXT]

**Trigger:** Any CSS rule that sets `min-width` (or allows intrinsic-size upward
propagation) on `html`, `body`, `.siteWrapper`, or any element that is an
ancestor of a `position: sticky` navigation bar.

**Why it's wrong:** The agent should NEVER set a min-width floor on the page root
or any ancestor of functional chrome. Min-width floors belong exclusively on the
*content area inner wrapper* — the innermost element that is a child of an
`overflow-x: auto` scroll container. Placing the floor anywhere higher breaks one
of two guarantees:

- If the page root has `overflow-x: hidden`: sticky nav breaks (hidden creates a
  scroll container, and sticky elements only stick relative to the scroll container,
  not the viewport).
- If the page root has no overflow constraint: the document grows to match the
  min-width, the sticky nav fills the widened document, and the page has no
  horizontal scroll at the root level — nav items are unreachable.

**The one safe location for a desktop min-width floor:**
```scss
// ✅ CORRECT — floor is deep inside the scroll container
.contentArea { overflow-x: auto; }           // scroll container
.contentAreaInner { min-width: 672px; }      // floor here, nowhere else

// ✅ CORRECT — wrapper clips without breaking sticky
.siteWrapper { overflow-x: clip; min-width: 0; }  // hard clip, no scroll container

// ❌ WRONG — floor on the wrapper that contains the nav
.siteWrapper { min-width: 672px; }

// ❌ WRONG — floor on html/body
html, body { min-width: 320px; }
```

**Viewport meta is also required:** Without `generateViewport` exporting
`width: "device-width"`, browser virtual viewports (default 980px) prevent
`max-width` media queries from firing at narrow desktop window widths, masking
this bug in development but exposing it in production or on precise-pointer
devices.

**Related:** AP-067, FB-147, FB-149, FB-[NEXT].
```

**Update the Category Index** to reflect AP-073:

```markdown
